GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 301
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/1/25
Short Title: Social Media Protections for Minors Under 16. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 6, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROVIDE SOCIAL MEDIA PROTECTIONS FOR MINORS UNDER SIXTEEN
3 YEARS OF AGE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. The General Statutes are amended by adding a new Chapter to read:
6 "Chapter 114B.
7 "Social Media Protections for Minors.
8 "§ 114B-1. Title; definitions.
9 (a) Title. – This Chapter shall be known and may be cited as the "Social Media Protection
10 for Minors Act."
11 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
12 (1) Account holder. – A person who opens an account or creates a profile or is
13 identified by the social media platform by a unique identifier while using or
14 accessing a social media platform when the social media platform knows or
15 has reason to believe the person is a resident of this State.
16 (2) Anonymous age verification. – A commercially reasonable method used by a
17 government agency or a business for the purpose of age verification, that is
18 conducted by a nongovernmental, independent third party organized under the
19 laws of a state of the United States that meets all of the following criteria:
20 a. Has its principal place of business in a state of the United States.
21 b. Is not owned or controlled by a company formed in a foreign country,
22 a government of a foreign country, or any other entity formed in a
23 foreign country.
24 (3) Daily active users. – The number of unique users in the United States who
25 used the online forum, website, or application at least eighty percent (80%) of
26 the days during the previous 12 months or, if the online forum, website, or
27 application did not exist during the previous 12 months, the number of unique
28 users in the United States who used the online forum, website, or application
29 at least eighty percent (80%) of the days during the previous month.
30 (4) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Justice.
31 (5) Minor. – A person who is under 16 years of age.
32 (6) Resident. – A person who lives in this State for more than six months of the
33 year.
34 (7) Social media platform or platform. – An online forum, website, or application
35 that satisfies all of the following criteria:
*H301-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Allows users to upload content or view the content or activity of other
2 users.
3 b. Ten percent (10%) or more of the daily active users who are younger
4 than 16 years of age spend on average two hours per day or longer on
5 the online forum, website, or application on the days when using the
6 online forum, website, or application during the previous 12 months
7 or, if the online forum, website, or application did not exist during the
8 previous 12 months, during the previous month.
9 c. Employs algorithms that analyze user data or information on users to
10 select content for users.
11 d. Has any of the following addictive features:
12 1. Infinite scrolling, which means either (i) continuously loading
13 content or content that loads as the user scrolls down the page
14 without the need to open a separate page or (ii) seamless
15 content or the use of pages with no visible or apparent end or
16 page breaks.
17 2. Push notifications or alerts sent by the online forum, website,
18 or application to inform a user about specific activities or
19 events related to the user's account.
20 3. Displays personal interactive metrics that indicate the number
21 of times other users have clicked a button to indicate their
22 reaction to content or have shared or reposted the content.
23 4. Auto-play video or video that begins to play without the user
24 first clicking on the video or on a play button for that video.
25 5. Live-streaming or a function that allows a user or advertiser to
26 broadcast live video content in real time.
27 The term does not include (i) an online service, website, or application where
28 the exclusive function is email or direct messaging consisting of text,
29 photographs, pictures, images, or videos shared only between the sender and
30 the recipients, without displaying or posting publicly or to other users not
31 specifically identified as the recipients by the sender, (ii) a community forum
32 where the primary purpose of the forum is for customer self-service support
33 related to products, sellers, services, events, or places, or any combination
34 thereof, (iii) an interactive video game service equipped with parental controls
35 that must be deactivated for a minor to use, (iv) online shopping, or (v)
36 e-commerce.
37 (8) Standard age verification. – Any commercially reasonable method of age
38 verification approved by the social media platform.
39 "§ 114B-2. Social media protections for minors.
40 (a) Minors Under 14 Years of Age. – A social media platform shall prohibit a minor who
41 is younger than 14 years of age from entering into a contract with the platform to become an
42 account holder and shall do all of the following:
43 (1) Terminate any account held by a minor under 14 years of age upon 30 days'
44 notice to the account holder. Termination must be effective upon the
45 expiration of the 30 days if the account holder fails to effectively dispute the
46 termination.
47 (2) Permanently delete all personal information held by the social media platform
48 relating to the terminated account, unless there are legal requirements to
49 maintain the information.
50 (b) Minors 14 or 15 Years of Age. – A social media platform shall prohibit a minor who
51 is 14 or 15 years of age from entering into a contract with the platform to become an account
Page 2 House Bill 301-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 holder unless the minor's parent or guardian provides consent for the minor to become an account
2 holder and shall do all of the following:
3 (1) Terminate any account held by an account holder who is 14 or 15 years of age
4 if the account holder's parent or guardian has not provided consent for the
5 minor to create or maintain the account. The social media platform shall
6 provide 30 days for an account holder to dispute the termination.
7 (2) Allow the parent or guardian of an account holder who is 14 or 15 years of
8 age to request that the minor's account be terminated. Termination must be
9 effective within 10 business days after the request.
10 (3) Permanently delete all personal information held by the social media platform
11 relating to the terminated account unless there are legal requirements to
12 maintain the information.
13 (c) Violations. – If the Department has reason to believe that a social media platform is
14 in violation of this section, the Department, as the enforcing entity, may bring an action against
15 the platform for an unfair or deceptive act or practice.
16 Any knowing or reckless violation of this section is deemed an unfair and deceptive trade
17 practice actionable under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes actionable solely by the Department
18 against a social media platform.
19 In addition to other remedies allowed by law, the Department may collect a civil penalty of
20 up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per violation and reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs.
21 When the social media platform's failure to comply with this section is a consistent pattern of
22 knowing or reckless conduct, punitive damages may be assessed against the platform.
23 A social media platform that knowingly or recklessly violates this section is liable to the
24 minor account holder, including court costs and reasonable attorneys' fees. Claimants may be
25 awarded up to ten thousand dollars ($10,000) in damages. Any action brought under this
26 paragraph may only be brought on behalf of a minor account holder. A civil action for a claim
27 under this paragraph must be brought within one year from the date the complainant knew, or
28 reasonably should have known, of the alleged violation.
29 If a social media platform allows an account holder to use the social media platform, the
30 parties have entered into a contract.
31 This section does not preclude any other available remedy at law or in equity.
32 For purposes of bringing an action under this section, a social media platform that allows a
33 minor to create an account on the platform is considered to be both engaged in substantial and
34 not isolated activities within this State and operating, conducting, engaging in, or carrying on a
35 business and doing business in this State, and is therefore subject to the jurisdiction of the courts
36 of this State.
37 (d) Enforcement. – If, by its own inquiry or as a result of complaints, the Department has
38 reason to believe that an entity or person has engaged in, or is engaging in, an act or practice that
39 violates this section, the Department may administer oaths and affirmations, subpoena witnesses
40 or matter, and collect evidence. Within five days, excluding weekends and legal holidays, after
41 the service of a subpoena or at any time before the return date specified therein, whichever is
42 longer, the party served may file in the superior court in the county in which it resides or in which
43 it transacts business and serve upon the enforcing authority a petition for an order modifying or
44 setting aside the subpoena. The petitioner may raise any objection or privilege which would be
45 available upon service of such subpoena in a civil action. The subpoena shall inform the party
46 served of its rights under this subsection.
47 If the matter that the Department seeks to obtain by subpoena is located outside the State, the
48 entity or person subpoenaed may make it available to the Department or its representative to
49 examine the matter at the place where it is located. The Department may designate
50 representatives, including officials of the state in which the matter is located, to inspect the matter
51 on its behalf, and may respond to similar requests from officials of other states.
