1 Upon failure of an entity or person without lawful excuse to obey a subpoena and upon
2 reasonable notice to all persons affected, the Department may apply to the superior court for an
3 order compelling compliance.
4 The Department may request that an entity or person that refuses to comply with a subpoena
5 on the ground that testimony or matter may incriminate the entity or person be ordered by the
6 court to provide the testimony or matter. Except in a prosecution for perjury, an entity or
7 individual that complies with a court order to provide testimony or matter after asserting a valid
8 privilege against self-incrimination shall not have the testimony or matter so provided, or
9 evidence derived therefrom, received against the entity or person in any criminal investigation or
10 proceeding.
11 Any entity or person upon whom a subpoena is served pursuant to this subsection shall
12 comply with the terms thereof unless otherwise provided by order of the court.
13 Any entity or person that fails to appear with the intent to avoid, evade, or prevent compliance
14 in whole or in part with any investigation under this Chapter or who removes from any place,
15 conceals, withholds, mutilates, alters, or destroys, or by any other means falsifies any
16 documentary material in the possession, custody, or control of any entity or person subject to any
17 such subpoena, or knowingly conceals any relevant information with the intent to avoid, evade,
18 or prevent compliance shall be liable for a civil penalty of not more than five thousand dollars
19 ($5,000) per week in violation, reasonable attorneys' fees, and costs.
20 (e) Rules. – The Department may adopt rules to implement this Chapter.
21 (f) Civil Penalties. – The clear proceeds of civil penalties provided for in this section
22 shall be remitted to the Civil Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
23 "§ 114B-3. Age verification for social media platforms.
24 (a) A social media platform must use either anonymous age verification or standard age
25 verification to verify that an account holder is 16 years of age or older and, except as provided in
26 G.S. 114B-2(b), prevent creation of an account by a person younger than 16 years of age. The
27 social media platform must offer anonymous age verification and standard age verification, and
28 a person attempting to create an account may select which method will be used to verify the
29 person's age.
30 (b) A social media platform must ensure that the requirements of subsection (c) of this
31 section are met.
32 (c) A third party conducting anonymous age verification pursuant to this section must
33 comply with all of the following:
34 (1) Shall not retain personal identifying information used to verify age once the
35 age of an account holder or a person seeking an account has been verified.
36 (2) Shall not use personal identifying information used to verify age for any other
37 purpose.
38 (3) Must keep anonymous any personal identifying information used to verify
39 age. The information may not be shared or otherwise communicated to any
40 person.
41 (4) Must protect personal identifying information used to verify age from
42 unauthorized or illegal access, destruction, use, modification, or disclosure
43 through reasonable security procedures and practices appropriate to the nature
44 of the personal information.
45 (d) Any violation of subsection (a) or (b) of this section is deemed an unfair and deceptive
46 trade practice actionable under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes solely by the Department on
47 behalf of a resident minor against a social media platform.
48 If the Department has reason to believe that a social media platform is in violation, the
49 Department may bring an action against the social media platform for an unfair or deceptive act
50 or practice under Chapter 75 of the General Statutes. In addition to other remedies allowed by
Page 4 House Bill 301-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 law, the Department may collect a civil penalty of up to fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per
2 violation and reasonable attorneys' fees and court costs.
3 When the social media platform's failure to comply with subsection (a) or (b) of this section
4 is a consistent pattern of knowing or reckless conduct, punitive damages may be assessed against
5 the social media platform.
6 "§ 114B-4. Miscellaneous provisions.
7 (a) It is the intent of the General Assembly that this Chapter be liberally construed for the
8 protection of minors.
9 (b) If any provision of this Chapter or its application to any person or circumstances is
10 held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this Chapter which
11 can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the provisions of
12 this Chapter are severable."
13 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
